<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-null-spaces"
    xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Null Spaces</title>
    <p>
        The <term>null space</term> or <term>kernel</term> of a <m>m \times n</m> matrix <m>A</m>
        is the solution space of the homogeneous system of equations <m>Ax = \mathbf 0</m>. 
        We denote this space <m>N(A)</m>, where
    </p>
    <md>
        <mrow> N(A) = \{x \in \R^n : Ax = \mathbf 0 \}. </mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
        The null space is a subspace of <m>\R^n</m>.
    </p>
    <subsection xml:id="subsec-manual-calculation-of-n">
        <title>Manual Calculation of the Kernel</title>
        <p>
            To calculate the null space of an <m>m \times n</m>
            matrix we must:
        </p>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Find the solution to the homogeneous system <m>Ax = \mathbf 0</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Write the solution 
                    <m>x = (d_1, d_2, \dots, d_k, f_1, \dots f_r)</m>
                    in the form <m>d_i= a_{i1} f_1 + a_{i2} f_2 + \dots +a_{ir} f_r</m>,
                    for <m> i=1...k </m>
                    where <m>f_1, f_2, \dots, f_r</m>
                    are the free variables and <m>k + r = n</m>.
                    Then the vectors:
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
        <md>
            <mrow> (a_{11}, a_{12}, \dots, a_{1r}, 1, 0, \dots, 0) </mrow>
            <mrow> (a_{21}, a_{22}, \dots, a_{2r}, 0, 1, \dots, 0) </mrow>
            <mrow> \vdots </mrow>
            <mrow> (a_{k1}, a_{k2}, \dots, a_{kr}, 0, 0, \dots, 1) </mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
             form a basis of <m>N(A)</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
            We do this in Sage by using the <c>solve</c> function.
        </p>
        <p>
            First we will initialize our variables and the matrix we will solve.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                var('x1, x2, x3')
                vars = [x1, x2, x3]
                A = matrix(QQ, [
                        [1, 2, 3], 
                        [4, 5, 6]
                    ])
                A
            </input>
        </sage>
        <p>
            Then we will decompose the matrix into the system
            of equations corresponding to <m>Ax = \mathbf 0</m>.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                eqs = [sum(A[i,j]*vars[j] for j in range(A.ncols())) == 0 
                       for i in range(A.nrows())]
                eqs
            </input>
        </sage>
        <p>
            Then we call <c>solve</c> to solve the equation.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                sol = solve(eqs, vars)
                sol
            </input>
        </sage>
        <p>
            By extracting the right hand side of the equation we get the parameterized solution vector.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                x_sol = vector([s.rhs() for s in sol[0]])
            </input>
            <output>
                
            </output>
        </sage>
        <p>
            By choosing values for these parameters, 
            we can identify the basis vector, <m>v</m>, of the null space.
            We preform this substitution with the <c>subs</c> method.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                v = x_sol.subs(r1=1)
                v
            </input>
            <output>
                
            </output>
        </sage>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-kernel-method">
        <title>Kernel Method</title>
        <p>
            Sage provides the <c>right_kernel</c> method to compute this subspace.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                V = VectorSpace(RR, 3)
                A = matrix(QQ,[
                         [1, 2, 3],
                         [4, 5, 6],
                     ])
                A
            </input>
        </sage>
        <sage>
            <input>
                N = A.right_kernel()
                N
            </input>
            <output>
                
            </output>
        </sage>
        <p>
            Sage returns the subspace <m>N</m> with its basis as a matrix.
        </p>
        <p>
            We can verify that N is a subspace of <m>\R^3</m>.
        </p>
        <sage>
            <input>
                N.is_subspace(V)
            </input>
        </sage>
    </subsection>
</section>